                <section class="exc-content">
            <div class="container">
                <div class="exc-container">
                                                                                                        <div class="content-item bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                                    <h2 class="title-content">How To Do</h2>
                                    <ol><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Sit on a bench or chair with your feet flat on the floor. Rest your forearm on your thigh or a bench, keeping your wrist over the edge.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Hold a dumbbell or barbell with an overhand grip, ensuring your palm faces downward.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Slowly lift your wrist upward, bringing the weight towards the ceiling. Keep your forearm stationary and your elbow slightly bent.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Gradually lower the weight back to the starting position. Maintain control throughout the movement to fully engage your muscles.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Complete the desired number of repetitions, usually 10–15 per set. Perform 2–3 sets, depending on your fitness level.</span></li></ol>                                                                    </div>
                                                                                                                                                            <div class="content-item bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                                    <h2 class="title-content">Tips From Expert</h2>
                                    <ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Avoid using too much weight to prevent jerky movements and ensure proper muscle engagement.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Make sure your forearm stays in place during the exercise. Focus on lifting your hand upward from the wrist (wrist extension).</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Don’t lift the weight too high to avoid straining your wrist. Stick to a controlled range of motion.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Keep your elbow slightly bent and wrist aligned with your forearm to reduce stress on the joints.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Perform a brief warm-up to prepare your wrists and forearms for the exercise.</span></li><li aria-level="1">Focus on maintaining proper form throughout each set. Consistent form helps maximize effectiveness and prevents overuse injuries.</li><li aria-level="1">Combine wrist extensions with <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC11012564/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">stretching exercises</a>. This combination can reduce soreness and enhance overall forearm flexibility. </li></ul>                                                                    </div>
                                                                                                                                                            <div class="content-item bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                                    <h2 class="title-content">Optimal Sets and Reps</h2>
                                    <p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Wrist extensions can be adjusted based on your training goals. Here’s </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7927075/#:~:text=A%20low%20repetition%20scheme%20with,of%201RM)%20optimizes%20hypertrophic%20gains" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">a guide</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> to setting up your workout:</span></p>                                                                                <div style="overflow: auto">
                                                <figure class="wp-block-table">
                                                    <table>
                                                        <thead>
