                                                                                                                                                            <div class="content-item bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                                    <h2 class="title-content">How to Put in Your Workout Split</h2>
                                    <p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Wrist extensions are essential for building forearm strength and improving wrist stability. This boosts grip strength, which is crucial for lifting heavier weights and </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8110677/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">preventing injuries</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">. They fit well into various workout splits, enhancing overall arm development.</span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Here are some ways to incorporate wrist extensions into your workout split:</span></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Full-Body Split</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> — Include wrist extensions at the end of your workout or perform them with your </span><a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/cooldown-exercises" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">cool-down exercises</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">. Perform 3–4 sets of 10–15 reps. This ensures forearm muscles are targeted after working other major muscle groups, promoting balanced arm development.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Upper/Lower Split</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> — On upper body days, include wrist extensions to enhance forearm strength and endurance. Perform 3–4 sets of 12–15 reps. On lower body days, adding wrist extensions can enhance grip strength and support exercises like deadlifts and dumbbell lunges.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Push/Pull/Legs Split</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> — Incorporate wrist extensions on pull days to complement back and bicep exercises. Perform 3–4 sets of 10–12 reps. This integration enhances grip strength and endurance, supporting pulling movements and overall arm strength.</span></li></ul>                                                                    </div>
