                        <div class="muscle-text bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                            <h3><b>Wrist Extensors</b></h3><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Wrist extensions primarily target the </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534805/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">wrist extensors</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">, which are muscles on the back of your forearm. These include the extensor carpi radialis longus and brevis, and extensor carpi ulnaris. They are crucial for lifting your hand, stabilizing the wrist, and bending it towards your thumb side. </span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Strengthening these muscles enhances grip strength, which is essential for lifting weights and handling everyday objects like tools and groceries. Improved grip strength not only boosts weightlifting performance but also supports activities that require firm hand control.</span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">During wrist extensions, the wrist extensors experience </span><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25289669/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">high activation</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> rates throughout the movement. Peak activation occurs towards the end of the contraction phase, at the top of the movement. High activation rates mean that wrist extensions effectively build extensor muscle strength and endurance.</span></p>                        </div>
