                        <div class="muscle-text bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                            <h3><b>Brachioradialis</b></h3><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526110/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">brachioradialis</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> muscle, located on the upper forearm, is activated during wrist extension exercises. It helps with bending the elbow and turning the forearm.</span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">When you perform wrist extensions, the brachioradialis assists by stabilizing the elbow and contributing to the movement. Its role becomes more pronounced towards the top of the movement.</span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">While it doesn’t do the main work, it helps maintain proper movement and support, increasing the benefits of the exercise. Strengthening this muscle improves overall forearm strength and can aid in other upper-body exercises.</span></p>                        </div>
